{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|かぶと}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=かぶと|-}}.  Found in the ''{{w|Nihon Shoki}}'' of 720 {{CE}} with the reading ''kaputo''.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref>

Derivation currently {{unk|ja|sort=かぶと|nocap=1}}.

* A surface analysis might suggest a derivation from {{m|ja|被る|tr=kaburu||to wear something on the head}}.  However, that reading derives from older form ''kagafuru'' and doesn't appear until 850,<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref> some time after the first appearance of ''kabuto''.

* An alternative analysis might suggest a compound of {{compound|ja|sort=かぶと|頭|tr1=kabu|t1=head|pos1=''[[kun'yomi]]'' and native Japanese term|兜|tr2=to|t2=helmet|pos2=''[[on'yomi]]'' and borrowing from Chinese}}.  However, the “[[head]]” sense with the ''kabu'' reading doesn't appear until near the end of the {{w|Muromachi period}}.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref>

